$ Internal vs external CSS

{ Inline CSS #inline-css

  The CSS style for a single → development/web/CSS/element can be assigned in an
  → development/web/HTML/tags[HTML tag's] → development/web/HTML/attributes#html-attr-style[`style` attribute].

code {
<div style='…'>
  text text
</div>
code }

}
{ Internal CSS

  The CSS styles that are to applied to a *single* → development/web/HTML document can be put into the same document using
  `→ development/web/HTML/tags/style[<style type='text/css'>…</style>`.

  gh|about-css|/inline_vs_external_css/use_inline_css.html||

}

{ External CSS

  If the same stylesheets are to be applied to *multiple* HTML documents, the can be refererenced from these HTML documents
  with → development/web/HTML/tags/link[`<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="path/to/file.css">`].

  A HTML document that references an external stylesheet file:
  gh|about-css|/inline_vs_external_css/use_external_css.html||

  In this example, the referenced stylesheet file is rather simple:
  gh|about-css|/inline_vs_external_css/external.css||

}

{ TODO

It seems possible to provide alternative stylesheets that the user can choose from using the ~View->Page Style~ menu (at least in Firefox):
code {
<link href="default.css"     rel="stylesheet"           title="Default"    >
<link href="big-letters.css" rel="alternate stylesheet" title="Big Letters">
<link href="contrast.css"    rel="alternate stylesheet" title="Contrast"   >
code }


}

sa:
  → development/web/HTML/tags/link[`<link>`] and
  → development/web/HTML/tags/style[`<style>`]

  → development/languages/JavaScript/inline-vs-external
